From: SeongJae Park <sj@kernel.org>
Date: Fri, 17 Apr 2026 07:48:34 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] ==== modules: fix stale status parameters ====

mm/damon/modules: fix stale status parameters

DAMON modules including DAMON_RECLAIM, DAMON_LRU_SORT and DAMON_STAT
commonly expose the running status and the pid of their kdamond via
'enabled' and 'kdamond_pid' parameters.  The code saves and updates the
information in variables when they start and stop the kdamond via
damon_start() and damon_stop().  It assumes kdamond will keep running
once started, until it is requested to be stopped.

But the kdamond can be stopped before damon_stop() is called.  It could
stop when regions_score_histogram allocation is failed, or
damon_commit_ctx() call for the running DAMON context fails due to
invalid parameters or internal allocation failures.  In the case, the
parameters are not updated and therefore expose the stale status.  It
could confuse users.  Worse yet, DAMON_RECLAIM and DAMON_LRU_SORT
strictly prohibit unnecessary damon_start() and damon_stop() calls,
based on the status parameters.  Hence, when the kdamond is stopped and
therefore the status variables be stale, DAMON_RECLAIM and
DAMON_LRU_SORT cannot start the kdamond again until the system is
reboot.  This can easily reproduced like below.

    # cd /sys/module/damon_reclaim/parameters
    # echo Y > enabled
    # echo 3 > addr_unit
    # echo Y > commit_inputs
    # echo 1 > addr_unit
    # echo Y > enabled

Note that the issue should only rarely happen because the allocation
failures are unlikely.  The allocations are arguably too small to fail.
Wrong parameters commit can easily reproduce the issue, but sane users
wouldn't do that in the real world product systems.

Fix the issues by detecting and using the real status when it is
necessary, instead of caching those under the wrong assumption.

Signed-off-by: SeongJae Park <sj@kernel.org>
